\begin_layout Section
Optimization approaches 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:07-Optimization_algorithms"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SHO-balancing problem has been tackled using three fundamentally different
 optimization algorithms, namely:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Differential evolution (see Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:02-DE"

\end_inset

), from the family of evolutionary algorithms;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Differential ant-stigmergy algorithm (see Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:02-DASA"

\end_inset

), from the family of swarm-intelligence algorithms; and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Simulated annealing (see Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:02-SA"

\end_inset

), from the family of classic metaheuristic algorithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each of these algorithms shall minimize the objective function value by
 adopting essentially disparate approaches, hence the diversity of applying
 algorithms belonging to different families to solve the same optimization
 problem.
 Therefore, the result analysis shall establish which of the presented approache
s is better suited for solving the SHO-balancing problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following sections describe how the SHO-balancing problem is represented
 by the internal structure of each of the selected algorithms and their
 controlling parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential evolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The DE algorithm features a parallel direct search method, which utilizes
 a population of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional parameter vectors.
 The SHO-balancing problem is expressed in each component of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of the population, which represents the pilot power of a target cell, i.e.:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{ag}=\left\{ x_{1},x_{2},\ldots x_{c},\ldots,x_{D}\right\} ,\label{eq:07-DE_mapping}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}\in P_{c}$
\end_inset

 represents a candidate pilot-power setting of cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 indicates the generation of an individual 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in the population.
 Since there are 
\begin_inset Formula $|C|$
\end_inset

 cells in a mobile network, it follows that the population size, 
\begin_inset Formula $D=|C|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the different variants of DE, the most popular one is used here, called
 
\emph on
DE/rand/1/bin
\emph default
.
 The nomenclature used to name this variant indicates the way the algorithm
 works:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
DE 
\emph default
denotes the differential evolution algorithm,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
rand 
\emph default
indicates that the individuals selected to compute the mutation values are
 randomly chosen,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
1
\emph on
 
\emph default
specifies the number of pairs of selected solutions used to calculate the
 crossover vector, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
bin 
\emph default
means that a binomial recombination operator is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential ant-stigmergy algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mapping between the balancing problem and the DASA is similar to the
 one for DE:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{a}=\left\{ x_{1},x_{2},\ldots x_{i},\ldots,x_{D}\right\} .\label{eq:07-DASA_mapping}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In this case, each ant, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, creates its own solution vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{a}$
\end_inset

, during the minimization process.
 At the end of every iteration, and after all the ants have created solutions,
 they are evaluated to establish if any of them is better than the best
 solution found so far.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simulated annealing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the SA perspective, the system under optimization is in a given 
\emph on
state
\emph default
 at each time step during the process.
 The objective function maps a system state to a value known as the 
\emph on
energy
\emph default
 of the system in that state.
 A 
\emph on
move
\emph default
 in the search space represents a change in the state of the system.
 Whether a move is performed or not depends on the values of the objective
 function and the temperature parameter (see Section
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:02-SA"

\end_inset

).
 After making a move, the system may exhibit lower or higher energy, depending
 on the current objective-function value.
\end_layout

